name: Marilyn I. Walker School of Fine and Performing Arts
directions: In the old Canada Hair Cloth building: second, third, and fourth floor provide unisex washrooms (single toilet, usually 2 to 3 rooms lined up next to one another), with one of the second-floor bathrooms being explicitly wheelchair accessible and located near the back entrance to the building (school is built on a hill: the second floor is ground-level at the back entrance). All unisex bathrooms are also located close to an elevator.
comment: The school culture is also pretty trans - friendly on the whole and most of the people working and studying there are unlikely to police anyone entering the gendered multi-stall bathrooms in the newer part of the building, unless someone is actively behaving in a way that warrants intervention. In short, any bathroom you find is likely to be safe, but the more private unisex option is most definitely available.

name: eBar
directions: Not physically accessible (so many stairs), however for many events they do make all of the washrooms unisex/gender neutral. Staff is supportive - if you have any issues I'm sure they would address them conscientiously. For events that have segregated washrooms by gender, there are other washrooms (closer to the cinema - if you walk through the greenroom towards the entrance above the bookshelf, there are washrooms right beside the cinema on the second floor). They tend to be a little more discreet and less busy than the main washrooms near the back of the venue.
comment: Events like Fierce and many of the Femme Rebelles Burlesque shows have gender neutral washrooms. Check event listings or call ahead to make sure.

name: Angelica Sweet Shop
directions: Ask whomever is working to direct you to the restroom. It is open to all.
comment: We welcome you!

name: Dstrct
directions: Second and third floor venue (above Van Goghs). Not physically accessible (sooo many stairs). On a usual night the bathrooms are segregated by gender, women's washroom tends to be fine (multiple private stalls), men's washroom has one stall which /sometimes/ has a door on it. Some events hosted here make both washrooms unisex. The owners are very supportive and I'm sure would address any issues re: accessibility or transphobia.
comment: ...not terrible?

Men's washroom is not great - doors often don't close entirely, big gaps, etc.
